Create one server-only `JazzContext` at process/app startup and reuse it across requests, jobs, and route handlers.

```ts
import { createJazzContext } from "jazz-tools/backend";
import { app } from "./schema";
import permissions from "./permissions";

export const jazz = createJazzContext({
  appId: process.env.JAZZ_APP_ID!,
  app,
  permissions,
  driver: { type: "persistent", dataPath: process.env.JAZZ_DATA_PATH ?? "./jazz-data" },
  serverUrl: process.env.JAZZ_SERVER_URL,
  backendSecret: process.env.BACKEND_SECRET,
  env: process.env.NODE_ENV === "production" ? "prod" : "dev",
  userBranch: "main",
});

process.once("SIGTERM", async () => {
  await jazz.shutdown();
  process.exit(0);
});
```

Important constraints: install `jazz-napi` as a direct dependency for Node.js; use a stable `dataPath` for persistent local state; do not create a context per request; call `shutdown()` during process termination to release native resources. A memory driver is ephemeral and needs an upstream `serverUrl`; it cannot be your only durable copy. Keep `BACKEND_SECRET` and `JAZZ_ADMIN_SECRET` server-only and never expose them through public framework environment variables. Use `backendSecret` when the backend connects to a sync server and needs backend/request-scoped authority such as `asBackend`, `forRequest`, `forSession`, or attribution helpers.

Use `null`, not `undefined`, when clearing an optional Jazz column. In an update payload, omitted keys and `undefined` mean “leave unchanged.”

```ts
db.update(app.todos, todoId, {
  projectId: null,
});
```

If code currently does something like `projectId: undefined`, that will preserve the existing `projectId`.

When query inputs are reactive, pass an accessor/function so the binding rebuilds the query when inputs change.

Svelte:
```ts
import { QuerySubscription } from "jazz-tools/svelte";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = new QuerySubscription(() =>
  app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId }).orderBy("title", "asc"),
);
```

Solid:
```ts
import { useAll } from "jazz-tools/solid";
import { app } from "./schema";

const todos = useAll(() => ({
  query: app.todos.where({ projectId: selectedProjectId() }).orderBy("title", "asc"),
}));
```

Passing an already-built query captures the current input value and will not track later changes.

Use `db.batch(...)` for two independent writes that should appear optimistically in the UI together. The batch commits locally after the callback returns and settles as one direct batch.

```ts
const result = db.batch((batch) => {
  batch.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  batch.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
await result.wait({ tier: "edge" });
```

Use `db.transaction(...)` when the two writes must stay staged until authority accepts them, then become globally visible together.

```ts
const result = await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  tx.update(app.todos, firstId, { done: true });
  tx.update(app.todos, secondId, { done: true });
});
await result.wait({ tier: "global" });
```

Build a thin typed layer at the Jazz row boundary, not by inventing generated table handles. Define schemas with `SchemaBuilder` and `TableSchema::builder`, write rows with `row_input!`, and treat `JazzClient::query(...)` as dynamic: it returns `(ObjectId, Vec<Value>)` in the exact projection order you requested.

Create one projection constant/function per application view and keep its decoder beside it. The decoder should reject wrong column counts, unexpected `Value` variants, and `Value::Null` where the schema is non-nullable. Example shape:

```rust
struct TodoRow {
    id: ObjectId,
    title: String,
    done: bool,
    description: Option<String>,
}

fn todo_query() -> QueryBuilder {
    QueryBuilder::new("todos")
        .select(["title", "done", "description"])
}

fn decode_todo(id: ObjectId, values: &[Value]) -> Result<TodoRow, AppError> {
    match values {
        [Value::Text(title), Value::Boolean(done), Value::Text(description)] => Ok(TodoRow {
            id,
            title: title.clone(),
            done: *done,
            description: Some(description.clone()),
        }),
        [Value::Text(title), Value::Boolean(done), Value::Null] => Ok(TodoRow {
            id,
            title: title.clone(),
            done: *done,
            description: None,
        }),
        _ => Err(AppError::SchemaDecode("todos projection mismatch")),
    }
}
```

For writes, expose typed command functions that convert domain input into Jazz values, call `insert`, `update`, or `delete`, and return the `BatchId` when callers need durability. Use transactions when multiple mutations must commit together. This keeps schema drift and invalid nullability failures centralized instead of scattering positional `Value` decoding through handlers.

Use one long-lived backend-connected `JazzClient` in service state, then scope it per request with the authenticated caller session. The backend credential authorizes the service transport role; the caller `Session` must drive row policy checks and write authorship.

Endpoint flow:

```rust
async fn update_todo(
    State(state): State<AppState>,
    AuthSession(session): AuthSession,
    Path(id): Path<ObjectId>,
    Json(input): Json<UpdateTodoRequest>,
) -> Result<Json<TodoRow>, AppError> {
    input.validate()?;

    let db = state.jazz.for_session(session);

    let batch = db.update(
        id,
        vec![
            ("title".into(), Value::Text(input.title)),
            ("done".into(), Value::Boolean(input.done)),
        ],
    )?;

    tokio::time::timeout(
        state.edge_timeout,
        db.wait_for_batch(batch, DurabilityTier::EdgeServer),
    )
    .await
    .map_err(|_| AppError::DurabilityTimeout)??;

    let rows = db.query(todo_by_id_query(id)).await?;
    let Some((row_id, values)) = rows.into_iter().next() else {
        return Err(AppError::NotFound);
    };

    Ok(Json(decode_todo(row_id, &values)?))
}
```

Map errors deliberately: invalid or missing auth to `401`, malformed input to `400`/`422`, absent or policy-filtered rows to `404`, policy rejection to `403`, durability timeout to `503`/`504`, and positional decoder mismatches to a safe internal error. Do not return success before `EdgeServer` or `GlobalServer` settlement if the route promises server-visible state.

Use a real `JazzServer` plus independent clients because the test covers auth, permissions, durability, authorship, and cross-client visibility. Build the schema and row policies through public builders, then exercise the production router rather than duplicating route code in the test.

Test sketch:

```rust
#[tokio::test]
async fn update_route_writes_as_caller_and_is_server_visible() {
    // 1. Start test JWT issuer and JazzServer with schema + row policies.
    // 2. Connect service JazzClient with backend credential and persistent or test storage.
    // 3. Start the production Axum router on an ephemeral listener, or call it through Tower.
    // 4. Connect user_a and user_b as independent Jazz clients.
    // 5. Seed a row as user_a with `row_input!`, then wait for `DurabilityTier::EdgeServer`.
    // 6. Call the real HTTP endpoint as allowed user_b.
    // 7. Query from a fresh independent client and select data plus provenance columns.
    // 8. Assert the updated value is visible, creator remains user_a, and updater is user_b.
    // 9. Call as denied user_c and assert `404` for filtered rows or `403` for rejected writes.
    // 10. Shut down route listener, clients, issuer, subscriptions, and server.
}
```

Use `wait_for_query` or a bounded retry helper for visibility instead of fixed sleeps. Assertions should inspect public behavior: route response, query results, settlement outcome, provenance columns, and cross-client visibility. Do not inspect internal history or transport state when those public observations prove the permission and authorship behavior.

Use a real local sync server and two memory clients. After Alice inserts several rows, wait for edge durability, then have Bob query them with an explicit ordering if order is product behavior. If order is not behavior, normalize by a stable key before asserting.

```ts
it("syncs several todos without depending on result order", async () => {
  const server = await startLocalJazzServer({ inMemory: true });
  let alice: Db | undefined;
  let bob: Db | undefined;

  try {
    await deploy({
      serverUrl: server.url,
      appId: server.appId,
      adminSecret: server.adminSecret,
      schema: app,
      permissions,
    });

    alice = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, adminSecret: server.adminSecret, driver: { type: "memory" } });
    bob = await createDb({ appId: server.appId, serverUrl: server.url, adminSecret: server.adminSecret, driver: { type: "memory" } });

    const rows = [
      { key: "a", title: "Alpha" },
      { key: "b", title: "Beta" },
      { key: "c", title: "Gamma" },
    ];

    await Promise.all(
      rows.map((row) => alice!.insert(app.todos, row).wait({ tier: "edge" })),
    );

    await vi.waitFor(async () => {
      const seen = await bob!.all(app.todos);
      expect(
        seen
          .map(({ key, title }) => ({ key, title }))
          .sort((left, right) => left.key.localeCompare(right.key)),
      ).toEqual(rows);
    });
  } finally {
    await alice?.shutdown();
    await bob?.shutdown();
    await server.stop();
  }
});
```

Key points: wait for Alice's writes at `tier: "edge"`, use `vi.waitFor` for eventual delivery to Bob, and sort or otherwise normalize results before comparing because query order is not under test.

Use `createPolicyTestApp` so the test exercises public permission behavior without needing a sync server. Assert denied reads by absence, and denied writes by rejection.

```ts
import { createPolicyTestApp, type PolicyTestApp } from "jazz-tools/testing";
import { afterEach, beforeEach, describe, expect, it } from "vitest";
import permissions from "../permissions";
import { app } from "../schema";

let testApp: PolicyTestApp;

beforeEach(async () => {
  testApp = await createPolicyTestApp(app, permissions, expect);
});

afterEach(async () => {
  await testApp.shutdown();
});

it("denies Bob read and write access to Alice's row", async () => {
  const alice = testApp.as({
    user_id: "alice",
    claims: {},
    authMode: "local-first",
  });
  const bob = testApp.as({
    user_id: "bob",
    claims: {},
    authMode: "local-first",
  });

  const todo = alice.insert(app.todos, { title: "Alice private todo" }).value;

  await expect(
    bob.all(app.todos.where({ id: todo.id })),
  ).resolves.toEqual([]);

  bob.expectDenied((db) =>
    db.update(app.todos, todo.id, { title: "Bob should not write" }),
  );

  alice.expectAllowed((db) =>
    db.update(app.todos, todo.id, { title: "Alice can write" }),
  );
});
```

This assumes the row policy makes Alice the owner via creator metadata or equivalent ownership logic. If the policy also restricts inserts or deletes, add separate allowed and denied assertions for those operations rather than treating update coverage as sufficient.
